1. INSTALLATION
---------------

1.1 SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS

    Operating System: Linux, macOS, or Windows
    Memory: Minimum 2GB RAM
    Storage: Minimum 100MB free space
    Dependencies: Rust toolchain (if building from source)

1.2 INSTALLING RUST

    If you don't have Rust installed:

    $ curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
    $ source "$HOME/.cargo/env"
    $ rustc --version

    Verify installation with:

    $ rustc --version

1.3 INSTALLING RAWSSG

    From crates.io (when published):

    $ cargo install rawssg

    From local source:

    $ git clone https://github.com/neuxdotdev/rawssg.git
    $ cd rawssg
    $ cargo install --path .

1.4 BUILDING FROM SOURCE

    $ git clone https://github.com/neuxdotdev/rawssg.git
    $ cd rawssg
    $ cargo build --release

    The binary will be at: ./target/release/rawssg

2. QUICK START
--------------

2.1 CREATING YOUR FIRST SITE

    $ rawssg init my-site
    $ cd my-site
    $ rawssg build
    $ rawssg serve

    Your site will be available at http://localhost:8080

2.2 BASIC COMMANDS

    Initialize a project:
    $ rawssg init [path]

    Build the site:
    $ rawssg build

    Build with minification:
    $ rawssg build --minify

    Watch for changes:
    $ rawssg build --watch

    Start development server:
    $ rawssg serve

    Create new content:
    $ rawssg new post "My First Post"
    $ rawssg new page "About" --draft

    Clean build output:
    $ rawssg clean

    Validate configuration:
    $ rawssg validate

2.3 PROJECT STRUCTURE

    After running `rawssg init`:

    my-project/
    │
    ├── .rawfile                    # Main configuration
    │
    ├── content/                    # All content files
    │   ├── index.rw               # Home page
    │   ├── about.rw               # About page
    │   └── posts/                 # Blog posts directory
    │       └── hello-world.rw
    │
    ├── templates/                  # Template files
    │   ├── base.html              # Main layout
    │   ├── _sidebar.html          # Sidebar partial
    │   ├── _content.html          # Content partial
    │   ├── _footer.html           # Footer partial
    │   └── static/
    │       ├── css/
    │       │   └── styles.css     # Default styles
    │       └── js/
    │           └── scripts.js     # Default JavaScript
    │
    └── dist/                       # Built site (generated)
        ├── index.html
        ├── about/
        │   └── index.html
        ├── posts/
        │   └── hello-world/
        │       └── index.html
        ├── css/
        │   └── styles.css
        ├── js/
        │   └── scripts.js
        ├── sitemap.xml
        ├── robots.txt
        └── feed.xml

3. CONFIGURATION
----------------

3.1 THE .RAWFILE FORMAT

    RawSSG uses a JSON configuration file named `.rawfile` at the project root.

    Minimal configuration:

    {
        "version": "0.1.0",
        "title": "My Site",
        "base_url": "https://example.com"
    }

    Full configuration:

    {
        "version": "0.1.0",
        "title": "My Site",
        "description": "A site built with RawSSG",
        "favicon": "favicon.ico",
        "base_url": "https://example.com",

        "content": {
            "format": "plain",
            "extensions": ["rw", "md"],
            "ignore": ["drafts/"],
            "drafts": false
        },

        "build": {
            "output_dir": "dist",
            "clean_build": false,
            "minify": {
                "html": false,
                "css": false,
                "js": false
            },
            "generate": {
                "sitemap": true,
                "robots": true,
                "feed": true
            },
            "strict": false
        },

        "template": {
            "dir": "templates",
            "default_layout": "base.html",
            "partials": ["sidebar", "content", "footer"]
        },

        "nav": [
            {
                "title": "Home",
                "url": "/"
            },
            {
                "title": "About",
                "url": "/about"
            },
            {
                "title": "Blog",
                "url": "/blog",
                "items": [
                    {
                        "title": "Recent Posts",
                        "url": "/blog/recent"
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],

        "footer": {
            "text": "Built with RawSSG",
            "links": [
                {
                    "title": "GitHub",
                    "url": "https://github.com/neuxdotdev"
                }
            ],
            "copyright": "© 2026 Your Name"
        },

        "custom": {
            "google_analytics": "UA-XXXXX-Y",
            "author": "Your Name"
        }
    }

3.2 CONFIGURATION OPTIONS

    Required fields:
        version: Must be "0.1.0"
        title: Site title
        base_url: Base URL for absolute links

    Optional fields:
        description: Site description for meta tags
        favicon: Path to favicon file
        content: Content processing settings
        build: Build process settings
        template: Template system settings
        nav: Navigation menu items
        footer: Footer configuration
        custom: Custom key-value pairs for templates

3.3 VALIDATION AND ERRORS

    Validate your configuration:

    $ rawssg validate

    Common validation errors:
        - Missing required fields
        - Invalid version
        - Invalid JSON syntax
        - File not found errors

    In strict mode (build.strict: true), additional validations:
        - Navigation items must have valid URLs
        - Required template files must exist
        - Frontmatter validation

4. CONTENT FORMAT
-----------------

4.1 .RW FILES EXPLAINED

    .rw files contain raw text content. They can include:
        - Optional YAML frontmatter (between --- delimiters)
        - Raw text content (after frontmatter)
        - Auto-detected links and emails

4.2 FRONTMATTER SYNTAX

    Frontmatter is optional YAML at the top of the file:

    ---
    title: Page Title
    slug: custom-slug
    date: 2026-01-01
    draft: false
    layout: custom-layout
    template: custom-template
    tags:
        - tag1
        - tag2
    categories:
        - category1
    custom_field: custom_value
    ---

    All frontmatter fields are optional. If no slug is provided,
    the filename is used. If no title is provided, the slug is used.

4.3 RAW CONTENT FORMAT

    After frontmatter (or at the start of the file if no frontmatter),
    write your content as plain text:

    This is raw text. It preserves whitespace and formatting.

    URLs are auto-linked: https://github.com/neuxdotdev
    Emails are auto-linked: neuxdev1@gmail.com

    No special formatting is applied. What you write is what you get.

4.4 SUPPORTED EXTENSIONS

    By default, RawSSG processes:
        - .rw files (recommended)
        - .md files (markdown, if enabled)

    Configure extensions in .rawfile:

    "content": {
        "extensions": ["rw", "txt", "md"]
    }

5. TEMPLATES
------------

5.1 TEMPLATE SYSTEM OVERVIEW

    RawSSG uses Handlebars templating engine. Templates are stored in
    the templates/ directory and compiled with your content.

5.2 BUILT-IN HELPERS

    Equality check:
        {{eq a b}} → true if a equals b

    Inequality check:
        {{neq a b}} → true if a not equals b

    Lowercase conversion:
        {{lowercase "TEXT"}} → "text"

    Date formatting:
        {{date "2026-01-01"}} → "January 1, 2026"

    Safe HTML output:
        {{variable | safe}} → Output raw HTML

5.3 PARTIALS AND LAYOUTS

    Default partials (in templates/ directory):
        _sidebar.html - Navigation sidebar
        _content.html - Content area
        _footer.html - Site footer

    Using partials in templates:
        {{> sidebar}}
        {{> content}}
        {{> footer}}

    Layout inheritance:
        Base template (base.html) includes partials
        Each page uses a layout (default: base.html)

5.4 CUSTOM TEMPLATES

    Create custom templates in templates/ directory:

    custom-page.html:
        <!DOCTYPE html>
        <html>
        <head>
            <title>{{title}}</title>
        </head>
        <body>
            <h1>{{title}}</h1>
            <div class="content">
                {{content}}
            </div>
        </body>
        </html>

    Specify template in frontmatter:
        ---
        title: Custom Page
        template: custom-page.html
        ---

6. BUILDING AND DEPLOYMENT
--------------------------

6.1 BUILD PROCESS

    Basic build:
        $ rawssg build

    Build with options:
        $ rawssg build --minify --clean

    The build process:
        1. Reads configuration from .rawfile
        2. Processes all content files in content/
        3. Applies templates
        4. Generates static files in dist/
        5. Creates sitemap.xml, robots.txt, feed.xml (if enabled)
        6. Copies static assets

6.2 DEVELOPMENT SERVER

    Start server:
        $ rawssg serve

    Server with watch mode:
        $ rawssg serve --watch

    Custom port:
        $ rawssg serve --port 3000

    The server uses Python's http.server by default.
    If Python is not available, it tries PHP's built-in server.

6.3 PRODUCTION DEPLOYMENT

    Build for production:
        $ rawssg build --minify

    Deploy to various platforms:

    Netlify:
        $ netlify deploy --dir=dist

    Vercel:
        $ vercel --prod

    GitHub Pages:
        # Push dist/ directory to gh-pages branch
        $ git subtree push --prefix dist origin gh-pages

    Cloudflare Pages:
        Connect repository and set build command:
        rawssg build --minify

    Any static hosting:
        Upload contents of dist/ directory

6.4 PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATION

    Enable minification:
        "build": {
            "minify": {
                "html": true,
                "css": true,
                "js": true
            }
        }

    Clean build (removes old files):
        $ rawssg build --clean

    Disable unused features:
        "build": {
            "generate": {
                "sitemap": false,
                "robots": false,
                "feed": false
            }
        }

7. TROUBLESHOOTING
------------------

7.1 COMMON ERRORS

    "No content files found":
        Create content/index.rw:
            $ mkdir -p content
            $ echo "Hello World" > content/index.rw

    "Config not found":
        Initialize project:
            $ rawssg init .

    "Template not found":
        Build to generate default templates:
            $ rawssg build

    "Invalid configuration":
        Validate configuration:
            $ rawssg validate

    "Server failed to start":
        Install Python 3 or PHP, or use custom port:
            $ rawssg serve --port 3000

7.2 DEBUG TIPS

    Enable verbose output:
        $ rawssg build --verbose

    Check file permissions:
        $ ls -la content/
        $ ls -la templates/

    Verify file encoding:
        $ file content/index.rw

    Check Rust version:
        $ rustc --version
        $ cargo --version

7.3 GETTING HELP

    Check documentation:
        https://github.com/neuxdotdev/rawssg

    File an issue:
        https://github.com/neuxdotdev/rawssg/issues

    Email support:
        neuxdev1@gmail.com

8. FAQ
------

8.1 GENERAL QUESTIONS

    Q: What does "raw" mean in RawSSG?
    A: Content remains as plain text without markdown or complex formatting.
       URLs and emails are auto-linked, but otherwise text is preserved as-is.

    Q: Why use RawSSG instead of other static site generators?
    A: RawSSG is minimal, fast, and focused on raw text content.
       It has zero dependencies in production and builds extremely quickly.

    Q: Is RawSSG suitable for blogs?
    A: Yes, with frontmatter support for metadata, dates, tags, and RSS feed generation.

    Q: Can I use RawSSG for documentation sites?
    A: Yes, the raw text format works well for technical documentation.

8.2 TECHNICAL QUESTIONS

    Q: Can I use custom CSS and JavaScript?
    A: Yes, place files in templates/static/css/ and templates/static/js/
       They will be copied to dist/ during build.

    Q: Can I add analytics tracking?
    A: Yes, add your analytics code to templates/base.html or use custom field.

    Q: How do I create nested pages?
    A: Create directories in content/:
        content/blog/post-1.rw → dist/blog/post-1/index.html

    Q: Can I use custom domains?
    A: Yes, set base_url in .rawfile and configure your domain with your hosting provider.

    Q: Is there image support?
    A: Place images in templates/static/images/ and reference them as /images/filename.jpg

8.3 USAGE QUESTIONS

    Q: How do I change the theme?
    A: Edit templates/static/css/styles.css or replace with your own CSS.

    Q: Can I disable the sidebar?
    A: Yes, edit templates/base.html and remove {{> sidebar}}.

    Q: How do I add social media links?
    A: Add to navigation or footer in .rawfile configuration.

    Q: Can I schedule posts for future dates?
    A: Use the date field in frontmatter and build when ready to publish.

    Q: How do I backup my site?
    A: Backup content/, templates/, and .rawfile files.

9. CONTRIBUTING
---------------

    Contributions are welcome!

    1. Fork the repository
    2. Create a feature branch
    3. Make your changes
    4. Run tests (cargo test)
    5. Submit a pull request

    Code standards:
        - Follow Rust conventions
        - Add documentation for new features
        - Include tests where applicable

    Report bugs:
        - Use the issue tracker
        - Include steps to reproduce
        - Provide error messages
